# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: buddhism-in-scotland
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] The **16th Karmapa, Rangjung Rigpe Dorje** (Tibetan: རང་འབྱུང་རིག་པའི་རྡོ་རྗེ་, Wylie: Rang 'byung rig pa'i rdo rje; August 14, 1924 – November 5, 1981) was the 16th Gyalwa Karmapa and the spiritual leader of the Karma Kagyu lineage of Tibetan Buddhism.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] He is of the oldest line of reincarnate lamas in Vajrayana Buddhism, known as the Karmapas whose coming was predicted by the Buddha in the Samadhiraja Sutra.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] The 16th Karmapa was considered to be a "living Buddha" and was deeply involved in the transmission of Tibetan Vajrayana Buddhism to Europe and North America following the Chinese invasion of Tibet.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] He was known as the "King of the Yogis", and is the subject of numerous books and films.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] The 16th Karmapa was born in Denkhok in the Kingdom of Derge in Kham eastern Tibet near the Dri Chu River (Ch.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] The previous Karmapa Khakyab Dorje (1871-1922) left a letter setting forth the circumstances of his next incarnation.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] The 15th Karmapa's close attendant, Jampal Tsultrim, possessed the letter of prediction, which matched exactly with the process the 11th Tai Situpa was already undertaking to find the 16th Karmapa, Rangjung Rigpe Dorje.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] Political obstacles arose in the recognition process of the 16th Karmapa, due to the delay of the prediction letter's arrival in Lhasa.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] Before Jampal Tsultrim could send a copy of the letter to the 13th Dalai Lama's government in Lhasa, a Lhasa Ministry issued a formal statement that the Karmapa’s reincarnation had been born in Lhasa as the son of one of its cabinet ministers, Lungshawa.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] Lungshawa wanted his son to be named as the Karmapa as part of his plan to modernize Tibet.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] The Karmapa's Labrang, where the Tsurphu Monastery's administration was located, appealed the decision saying that they had an authentic prediction letter.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] The Ministry replied that the Dalai Lama had issued a position, which couldn't be changed.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] The petitioning went back and forth for a year until Lungshawa's son fell from a roof, broke his pelvis and died from ensuing complications.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] The Tsurphu Monastery re-submitted the Karmapa's name but were again rebuffed by the Ministry, since submitting a single name was equivalent to the Tsurphu Monastery choosing the tulku.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] The 1st Beru Khyentse Rinpoche came up with a plan to submit the Karmapa's name twice - once as the son of the father, and a second time as the son of the mother.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] The Ministry responded by saying the correct tulku was the mother's son, not the father's son.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] He was taken to the Palpung Monastery where the 11th Tai Situpa, Pema Wangchok, gave him ordination, the Bodhisattva vows and many teachings.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] Beru Khyentse Lodro Miza Pampa'i Gocha taught him the tantras.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] Bo Kangkar Rinpoche taught him the sutras.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] Jamgon Palden Kyentse Oser taught him Mahamudra and the Six Yogas of Naropa.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] He regarded the 11th Tai Situpa, Pema Wangchok, and the 2nd Jamgön Kongtrül Khyentse Öser as his root gurus.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] In 1931, at the age of seven, he performed his first Black Crown ceremony.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] He received his hair cutting ceremony at age thirteen from Thubten Gyatso, 13th Dalai Lama.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] During his education, he received all the Kagyu transmissions and was also taught by the Sakya Trizin for many years.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] In the beginning of 1940, he went into retreat, and in 1947, started a pilgrimage to India, before another one in 1956 together with Tenzin Gyatso, the 14th Dalai Lama.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] Rangjung continued his education with the 10th Mindrolling Trichen of the Nyingma School and it was concluded with the Kalachakra initiation of the Gelugpa School.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] Rangjung had therefore received all the major teachings of all the major Tibetan Buddhist schools.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] The 16th Karmapa continued his predecessor's activities, travelling and teaching throughout Tibet, Bhutan, Nepal, Sikkim, India and parts of China.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] His activity also included locating the rebirths of high reincarnate lamas spontaneously, without meditation.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] Prior to the Chinese invasion of Tibet the Karmapa made a series of predictions indicating that the Tibetan people would need to be prepared to escape to India.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] As political circumstances altered Tibet radically with the 1950 takeover by China.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] The Karmapa, along with the Dalai Lama, government officials, and other high lamas, attended talks in Beijing to negotiate a settlement.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] This succeeded for a while, but in 1959 the Chinese government insisted on land reform, which would undermine the system of independent monasteries in Tibetan Buddhism.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] Conflict with the lamas as spiritual leaders accelerated.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] In February of that year Karmapa took 160 students from Tsurphu Monastery and escaped to Bhutan, taking the lineage's most sacred treasures and relics with them.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] Tashi Namgyal, the King of Sikkim, offered the Karmapa the site where the 9th Karmapa had previously established one of three Sikkim monasteries, which was then in ruins.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] It was here that the 16th Karmapa's seat-in-exile, Rumtek Monastery, was built then officially inaugurated in 1966.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] The traditional Tibetan seat of the Karmapa, Tsurphu Monastery, from where the Karmapa Ogyen Trinley Dorje escaped in 1999, still exists while the number of monks is restricted by the Chinese government.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] In the beginning of the 1970s the Karmapa made the prediction that Tibet would have a hard struggle gaining independence and even if it did, it would not allow the refugees to return.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] Rumtek would not be a good place either, and although Sikkim and Bhutan are still stable, they can deteriorate as well.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] However the Western world will embrace Buddhism, so he sent Lama Gendün to Europe.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] In 1974, with the help of Freda Bedi, he embarked on his first world tour.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] On September 15, The Karmapa left Rumtek with an entourage of Tulkus and monks, including Tenga Rinpoche, Bardor Tulku Rinpoche and Lama Jigme Rinpoche.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] He was welcomed in London September 17, by Chime Rinpoche, Akong Rinpoche and others, including Hannah Nydahl and Lama Ole Nydahl.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] The Karmapa traveled to Europe, Canada and the United States, where he was welcomed by Chögyam Trungpa.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] In October 1974 The Karmapa visited the Second Mesa, Hopi reservation in Arizona.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] He established Dhagpo Kagyu Ling in France as the central seat of activity, gave several Black Crown ceremonies, and attended an audience granted by Pope Paul VI.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] In 1976-77 he began a more exhaustive tour, giving extensive teachings, visiting nearly every major city in Europe.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] In May 1980, Karmapa again visited the West, stopping for lectures and ceremonies in London, New York, San Francisco, Santa Cruz, Boulder, and Santa Fe.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] The sixteenth Karmapa helped foster the transmission of Tibetan Buddhism to the West.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] He established Dharma centers and monasteries in various places around the world in order to protect, preserve, and spread Buddha's teachings.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] As part of an initiative by the Tibetan government-in-exile to consolidate the organizations of Tibetan Buddhism, Rangjung Rigpe Dorje became the first formal head of the Kagyu School, although the earlier Karmapas had long been considered the most prestigious and authoritative lamas of that school.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] There are several accounts of miracles performed by the 16th Karmapa, which is in keeping with many Buddhist masters that came before him.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] The Karmapa's identity as a child was kept secret, but nearby villagers noticed auspicious signs at his birth and came to him for blessings.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] As a child the Karmapa exhibited clairvoyant abilities, and if local peasants lost a sheep or another animal from their flock he knew where their animals were.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] Karmapa, who was fond of birds, was said to bless them upon their death.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] Instead of keeling over they would remain completely stiff and remain upwards for several days.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] It was understood that the birds were in a state of samadhi, and this process was known as "liberation through contact".
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] In 1974 the Karmapa visited the Hopi tribe in New Mexico, who had requested him to relieve their drought-stricken land.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] He conducted a ceremony, and a deluge of rain fell for the first time in seventy-five days.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] In the evening, Hopi and Navajo people were granted the empowerment of Red Chenrezig.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] In 1980-81 the Karmapa began his last world tour, giving teachings, interviews and empowerments in South East Asia, Greece, Great Britain, Canada and the United States.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] Rangjung Rigpei Dorjé died on November 5, 1981, in the United States in a hospital in Zion, Illinois, just north of Chicago.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] Doctors and nurses at the hospital remarked on his kindness and how he seemed more concerned with their welfare than his own.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] According to buddhism-affiliated sources, one doctor was also struck by the Karmapa's refusal of pain medication and the absence of any signs of feeling the profound pain that most patients in his condition report.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] Upon his death, against hospital procedure but in keeping with Tibetan tradition and with special permission from the State of Illinois, his body was left in the hospital for three days.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] His body was cremated at Rumtek, also according to Tibetan tradition.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] Like his predecessors, he was primarily a spiritual figure and therefore not involved in politics.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] He instead made efforts to keep the spiritual traditions of Tibet intact and in this way helped to preserve the identity of Tibet as a unique and individual culture.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/16th-karmapa] Rangjung Rigpe Dorje, as with all other Karmapas and tulkus, is accepted by Tibetan Buddhists as a manifestation of an enlightened being.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] The **1959 Tibetan uprising** or **Lhasa uprising** began on 10 March 1959 as a series of protests in the Tibetan capital of Lhasa, fueled by fears that the government of the People's Republic of China planned to arrest the Dalai Lama.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Over the next ten days, the demonstrations evolved from expressions of support for the 14th Dalai Lama to demands for independence and the reversal of the 1951 Chinese annexation of Tibet.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] After protesters acquired weapons, China's People's Liberation Army (PLA) shelled protesters in the Dalai Lama's summer palace and deployed tanks to suppress the demonstrations.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Bloody fighting continued for the next three days while the Dalai Lama escaped to India.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Thousands of Tibetans were killed during the 1959 uprising, but the exact number is disputed.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] The CIA provided extensive support to the uprising, including training for Tibetan fighters, logistical assistance through camps based in Nepal, and the organization of several aerial supply missions.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Earlier in 1956, armed conflict between Tibetan guerrillas and the PLA started in the Kham and Amdo regions, which had been subjected to socialist reform.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Guerrilla warfare later spread to other areas of Tibet and lasted through 1962.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Some regard the Xunhua Incident in 1958 as a precursor of the Tibetan uprising.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] The 10 March anniversary of the uprising is observed by exiled Tibetans as Tibetan Uprising Day and Women's Uprising Day.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] On 19 January 2009, the PRC-controlled legislature in the Tibet Autonomous Region chose 28 March as the national anniversary of Serfs Emancipation Day.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Smith Jr. describes the move as a "counter-propaganda" celebration following the 10 March 2008 unrest in Tibet.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] In 1951, the Seventeen Point Agreement between the People's Republic of China (PRC) and representatives of the Dalai Lama was put into effect.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Socialist reforms such as redistribution of land were delayed in Tibet proper.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] However, eastern Kham and Amdo (western Sichuan / Xikang and Qinghai provinces in the Chinese administrative hierarchy) were outside the administration of the Tibetan government in Lhasa, and were thus treated more like other Chinese provinces, with land redistribution implemented in full.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] The Khampas and nomads of Amdo traditionally owned their own land.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Armed resistance broke out in Amdo and eastern Kham in June 1956.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Prior to the PLA invasion, relations between Lhasa and the Khampa chieftains had deteriorated, although the Khampa remained spiritually loyal to the Dalai Lama throughout.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Because of these strained relations, the Khampa had actually assisted the Chinese communists in their initial invasion, before becoming the guerrilla resistance they are now known for.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Pandatsang Rapga, a pro-Kuomintang and pro-Republic of China Khampa revolutionary leader, offered the governor of Chamdo, Ngabo Ngawang Jigme, some Khampa fighters in exchange for the Tibetan government recognizing the independence of Kham.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] After the defeat of the Tibetan Army in Chamdo, Rapga started mediating in negotiations between the PRC and the Tibetan rebels.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Rapga and Topgay engaged in negotiations with the Chinese during their assault on Chamdo.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Khampas either defected to the Chinese PLA forces or did not fight at all.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Resistance fighters' attacks and People's Liberation Army reprisals against Khampa resistance groups such as the Chushi Gangdruk became increasingly brutal.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Kham's monastic networks came to be used by guerrilla forces to relay messages and hide rebels.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Punitive strikes were carried out by the Chinese government against Tibetan villages and monasteries.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Tibetan exiles assert that threats to bomb the Potala Palace and the Dalai Lama were bluffs made by Chinese military commanders in an attempt to intimidate the guerrilla forces into submission.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Lhasa continued to abide by the seventeen-point agreement and sent a delegation to Kham to quell the rebellion.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] After speaking with the rebel leaders, the delegation instead joined the rebellion.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Kham leaders contacted the Central Intelligence Agency (CIA), but the CIA under President Dwight D.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Eisenhower insisted it required an official request from Lhasa to support the rebels.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Eventually the CIA began to provide covert support for the rebellion without word from Lhasa.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] By then the rebellion had spread to Lhasa which had filled with refugees from Amdo and Kham.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Opposition to the Chinese presence in Tibet grew within the city of Lhasa.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] The next day, the Chinese leader saw a report from the PLA General Staff's Operations Department describing rebellions by Tibetans in Sichuan, Yunnan, Gansu, and Qinghai.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] He again stressed that "rebellions like these are extremely favorable for us because they will benefit us in helping to train our troops, train the people, and provide a sufficient reason to crush the rebellion and carry out comprehensive reforms in the future".
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] The PLA used Hui soldiers, who formerly had served under Ma Bufang to crush the Tibetan revolt in Amdo.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Hui cavalry were stationed in Southern Kham.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] The situation in all of Tibet became increasingly tense, as a growing number of Tibetans began to support the Khampa uprising, while "anti-Chinese communist agitation" spread among the Tibetans.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] The regional government in Lhasa neither wanted to back a rebellion nor publicly oppose it.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Dissatisfied, the Chinese Communist Party put pressure on the Dalai Lama's government to join the operations against the rebels, and made it increasingly clear that a spread of the insurgency would lead to "all-out repression" in Tibet.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] In this unstable situation, the Chinese generals resident in Lhasa was summoned back to mainland China, leaving the inexperienced PLA commander Tan Guansan in charge, just as the date of the Monlam Prayer Festival approached.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] This festival had previously been used by participants to voice "anti-Chinese sentiments".
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] According to historian Tsering Shakya, the Chinese government was pressuring the Dalai Lama to attend the National People's Congress in April 1959, in order to repair China's image in relation to ethnic minorities after the Khampa rebellion.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] According to the Dalai Lama's memoirs, the invitation came from Chinese General Zhang Jingwu, who proposed that the performance be held at the Chinese military headquarters; the Dalai Lama claimed that he had agreed.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] However, Tibetologist Sam van Schaik stated that the Dalai Lama was the one who proposed that the dance should take place in the military headquarters as the Norbulingka was too small.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Both parties did not yet agree on a date, and the Dalai Lama seemed to put the event "out of his mind", focusing instead on his ongoing examinations for his Geshe degree as well as the Monlam Prayer Festival.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Besides Tan and the Dalai Lama, nobody was seemingly informed of the plans for the dance.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] As a result, the date for the planned performance was only finalized 5 or 3 days beforehand when Tan reminded the Dalai Lama of the dance; the latter then suggested 10 March.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] The decision was seemingly concluded on a whim.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Neither the Kashag nor the Dalai Lama's bodyguards were informed of the Dalai Lama's plans until Chinese officials briefed them on 9 March, one day before the performance was scheduled, and insisted that they would handle the Dalai Lama's security.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Some members of the Kashag were alarmed and concerned that the Dalai Lama might be abducted, recalling a prophecy that told that the Dalai Lama should not exit his palace.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] According to historian Tsering Shakya, some Tibetan government officials feared that plans were being laid for a Chinese abduction of the Dalai Lama, and spread word to that effect amongst the inhabitants of Lhasa.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] On 10 March, several thousand Tibetans surrounded the Dalai Lama's palace to prevent him from leaving or being removed.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] The huge crowd had gathered in response to a rumor that the Chinese were planning to arrest the Dalai Lama when he went to a cultural performance at the PLA's headquarters.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] This marked the beginning of the uprising in Lhasa, though Chinese forces had skirmished with guerrillas outside the city in December of the previous year.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] The protesters publicly pleaded that the Dalai Lama should not attend the meeting with the Chinese officials, claiming that he would be kidnapped.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Although CCP officials insisted that the "reactionary upper stratum" in Lhasa was responsible for the rumor, there is no way to identify the precise source.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] At first, the violence was directed at Tibetan officials perceived not to have protected the Dalai Lama or to be pro-Chinese; attacks on Chinese started later.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] One of the first casualties of the mob was a senior lama, Pagbalha Soinam Gyamco, who worked with the PRC as a member of the Preparatory Committee of the Tibet Autonomous Region, who was killed and his body dragged by a horse in front of the crowd for 2 kilometres (1.2 mi).
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] The protesters also began to use openly anti-Chinese slogans such as "The Chinese must go, leave Tibet to Tibetans".
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] As protests and violence spread, the Dalai Lama informed the protesters that he would stay at the palace, yet this was no longer enough for the growing crowd.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Protesters began to demand Tibetan independence, and urged the Dalai Lama's government to publicly endorse their actions.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Barricades went up on the streets of Lhasa, and Chinese government soldiers and Tibetan rebel forces began to fortify positions within and around Lhasa in preparation for conflict.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] A petition of support for the armed rebels outside the city was taken up, and an appeal for assistance was made to the Indian consul.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Chinese and Tibetan troops continued moving into position over the next several days, with Chinese artillery pieces being deployed within range of the Dalai Lama's summer palace, the Norbulingka.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] On 12 March thousands of women gathered in front of the Potala Palace in Lhasa on the ground called Dri-bu-Yul-Khai Thang.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] The leader of this nonviolent demonstration was Pamo Kusang.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] This demonstration, now known as Women's Uprising Day, started the Tibetan women's movement for independence.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] After consulting the state oracle and concluding that the situation had become too unstable, the Dalai Lama and his close confidants opted to flee Lhasa.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] On 15 March, preparations for the Dalai Lama's evacuation from the city were set in motion, with Tibetan troops being employed to secure an escape route from Lhasa.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] On 17 March, two artillery shells landed near the Dalai Lama's palace, triggering his flight into exile.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] The Dalai Lama secretly left the palace the following night and slipped out of Lhasa with his family and a small number of officials.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] The Chinese had not strongly guarded the Potala, as they did not believe it likely that the Dalai Lama would try to flee.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] After reaching Lhoka, the Dalai Lama linked up with Kham rebels who began protecting him and upon reaching Lhotse at the Indian border, he proclaimed the restoration of Tibet's independence.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Rumours about the Dalai Lama's disappearance began to spread rapidly on the next day, though most still believed that he was in the palace.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Meanwhile, the situation in the city became increasingly tense, as protesters had seized a number of machine guns.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] At this point, remnants of the Tibetan Army had joined the protesters' ranks.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] On 20 March, the Chinese army responded by shelling the Norbulingka to disperse the crowd, and placed its troops at a barricade that divided the city into a northern and southern part in the following night.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] The battle began early on the following day and proved to be "bloody".
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Fighting in the streets continued for the next three days.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] The last Tibetan resistance was centered on the Jokhang, where Khampa refugees had set up machine guns, while a large number of Tibetans circumambulated the temple in reverence.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] The PLA started to attack the Jokhang on 23 March, and a hard-fought, three hours-long battle with many casualties on both sides ensued.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] The Chinese eventually managed to break through using a tank, whereupon they raised the flag of China on the temple, ending the uprising.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Lhasa's streets were reportedly littered with corpses, and at least 4,000 people were arrested.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Two British writers, Stuart and Roma Gelder, visited the Chensel Phodrang palace in the Norbulingka in 1962 and "found its contents meticulously preserved".
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] The Indian government under Nehru expressed concerns of the Tibetan people and condemned China as an aggressive power due to the violent suppression of the revolt by the PLA.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Pandatsang Rapga, a pro-Kuomintang and pro-Republic of China revolutionary Khampa leader, was instrumental in the revolt against the communists.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] The Kuomintang had a history of using Khampa fighters to oppose both the Dalai Lama's Tibetan government, and battle the Chinese Red Army.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Rapga continued to cooperate with the ROC government after it fled to Taiwan.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] The ROC government disagreed with the US government on whether Tibet should be independent, since the ROC claimed Tibet as part of its territory.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Rapga agreed to a plan in which the revolt against the communists would include anti feudalism, land reform, a modern government, and to give power to the people.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] However, the Dalai Lama's first visit to Taiwan in 1997 was said to have somewhat improved the two communities' general relationship, although "tension" allegedly still exists between them due to considerable differences.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] The Dalai Lama's visit also allowed for Tibetans to visit Taiwan without directly contacting the Mongolian and Tibetan Affairs Commission, and some Tibetans in Taiwan (such as Changa Tsering, an incumbent MTAC committee member) subsequently attended the celebration of the Dalai Lama's visit in 1997.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] The Tibetan community in Taiwan was also formerly divided between loyalty to the Dalai Lama and Taiwan's MTAC, although the MTAC was formally dissolved in 2017.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] The employees and responsibilities of the commission were thus officially reassigned to two places: the Mongolian and Tibetan Cultural Center under the Ministry of Culture, and the expanded Department of Hong Kong, Macao, Inner Mongolia, and Tibet Affairs under the Mainland Affairs Council.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Tibetologist Tom Grunfeld said "the veracity of such a claim is difficult to verify".
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Smith, a writer with Radio Free Asia, writes that the "secret documents" came from a 1960 PLA report captured by guerrillas in 1966, with the figures first published by the TGIE in India in 1990.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Smith states that the documents said that 87,000 "enemies were eliminated", but he does not take "eliminated" to mean "killed", as the TGIE does.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] The Peace Research Institute Oslo (PRIO) estimated 10,000 Tibetan and 2,000 PLA battle deaths.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Lhasa had a population of sixty to seventy thousand at the time.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Estimates covering 1956–59 including areas outside Lhasa put civilian deaths at around 60,000 and military deaths at around 40,000.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Following the uprising, the Chinese government launched a wide-reaching campaign to consolidate control and implement socialist reforms across Tibet.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Lhasa's three major monasteries - Sera, Ganden, and Drepung were heavily damaged by shelling, with Sera and Drepung reportedly left nearly beyond repair.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] According to the TGIE, members of the Dalai Lama's bodyguard who were remaining in Lhasa were disarmed and publicly executed, along with Tibetans who were found to be harbouring weapons in their homes.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Thousands of Tibetan monks were executed or arrested, and monasteries and temples around the city were looted or destroyed.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] After the 12 March Women's Uprising demonstration, many of the women who were involved in it were imprisoned, including the leader of the demonstration, Pamo Kusang.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] "Some of them were tortured, died in prison, or were executed." Known as Women's Uprising Day, this demonstration started the Tibetan women's movement for independence.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Meanwhile, the CIA continued to support Tibetan resistance from 1957 to 1972, training agents in the United States and inserting them into Tibet to organize rebellions against the People's Liberation Army (PLA).
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] CIA officer Bruce Walker, who oversaw the program, later expressed concern about the hostility that the radio teams encountered from the local population inside Tibet, with at least one group reportedly betrayed by his own brother, and all three agents were arrested.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Despite the arrests, those agents were not mistreated and were later released across the Indian border after undergoing less than a month of propaganda sessions.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] In April 1959, the 19-year-old Panchen Lama, the second ranking spiritual leader in Tibet, residing in Shigatse, called on Tibetans to support the Chinese government.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] However, after a tour through Tibet in May 1962, he wrote a document which is known as the 70,000 Character Petition.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] The document was addressed to Zhou Enlai and in it, he criticized Chinese abuses in Tibet.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Shortly afterward, he met with Zhou in order to have a discussion about the document.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] The outlined petition dealt with the brutal suppression of the Tibetan people both during and after the PLA's invasion of Tibet and the sufferings of the people in The Great Leap Forward.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] In this document, he criticized the suppression that the Chinese authorities had conducted in retaliation for the 1959 Tibetan uprising.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] But in October 1962, the PRC authorities who were dealing with the population criticized the petition.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Chairman Mao called the petition "... a poisoned arrow shot at the Party by reactionary feudal overlords." In 1967, the Panchen Lama was formally arrested and imprisoned until his release in 1977.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] In June 1959, the Buddhist monk Palden Gyatso was arrested for demonstrating during the March uprising by Chinese officials.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] He spent the next 33 years in Chinese prisons and laogai or "reform through labor" camps, the longest term of any Tibetan political prisoner.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] He was tortured, including with a cattle prod that was activated in his mouth and which led to the loss of his teeth.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] As part of the occupation of Tibet, in July 1959, the PLA occupied several Bhutanese enclaves in western Tibet which were under Bhutanese administration for more than 300 years, having been ceded to Bhutan by Ngawang Namgyal in the 17th century.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] These included Darchen, Labrang Monastery, Gartok and several smaller monasteries and villages near Mount Kailas.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Chinese authorities have interpreted the uprising as a revolt by the Tibetan elite against socialist reforms that were improving the lives of Tibetan serfs.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Tibetan exile sources and some independent sources, on the other hand, have usually interpreted it as a popular uprising against Chinese rule.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Historian Tsering Shakya has argued that the revolt reflected widespread dissatisfaction both with the Chinese authorities and also with the Tibetan government in Lhasa, which was seen as unable to protect the Dalai Lama's authority and Tibetan sovereignty.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] The Dalai Lama, fearing for his safety, fled Lhasa on March 17, 1959, and eventually found refuge in India.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] Upon reaching India, he and his followers were granted asylum by the Indian government, marking the beginning of his exile.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] From his residence in Dharamshala, Himachal Pradesh, the Dalai Lama played a major role in promoting Tibetan Buddhism internationally and raising awareness of the Tibetan cause.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/1959-tibetan-uprising] According to Chope Paljor Tsering, a former minister in the Central Tibetan Administration, “Buddhism has not only survived, but been revived and appreciated... by many cultures around the world,” suggesting that the Dalai Lama has helped reshape global perceptions of Buddhism.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] A nationwide census, known as **Census 2001**, was conducted in the United Kingdom on Sunday, 29 April 2001.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] This was the 20th UK census and recorded a resident population of 58,789,194.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The 2001 UK census was organised by the Office for National Statistics (ONS) in England and Wales, the General Register Office for Scotland (GROS) and the Northern Ireland Statistics and Research Agency (NISRA).
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Detailed results by region, council area, ward and output area are available from their respective websites.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Similar to previous UK censuses, the 2001 census was organised by the three statistical agencies, ONS, GROS, and NISRA, and coordinated at the national level by the Office for National Statistics.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The Orders in Council to conduct the census, specifying the people and information to be included in the census, were made under the authority of the Census Act 1920 in Great Britain, and the Census Act (Northern Ireland) 1969 in Northern Ireland.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] In England and Wales these regulations were made by the Census Order 2000 (SI 744/2000), in Scotland by the Census (Scotland) Order 2000 (SSI 68/2000), and in Northern Ireland by the Census Order (Northern Ireland) 2000 (SRNI 168/2000).
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The census was administered through self-completion forms, in most cases delivered by enumerators to households and communal establishments in the three weeks before census night on 29 April.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] For the first time return by post was used as the main collection method, with enumerators following up in person where the forms were not returned.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The postal response rate was 88% in England and Wales, 91% in Scotland, and 92% in Northern Ireland.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] A total of 81,000 field staff were employed across the UK (70,000 in England and Wales, 8,000 in Scotland and 3,000 in Northern Ireland).
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The census was conducted at the height of the foot-and-mouth crisis, which led to extra precautions being adopted by the field staff, and suggestions that the census may have to be postponed.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] However, it was reported that the disease outbreak did not affect the effectiveness of the collection process.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The census was estimated to cost £259m over its 13-year cycle from the start of planning in 1993 to the delivery of final results in 2006.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Printing of the 30 million census forms was subcontracted to Polestar Group, and processing of the returned census forms was subcontracted to Lockheed Martin in a contract worth £54m.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The forms were initially scanned into digital format, then read with OMR and OCR, with manual entry where the automatic process could not read the forms.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The forms were then pulped and recycled, and the digital copies printed onto microfilm for storage and release after 100 years.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Once the data were returned to the statistics agencies it underwent further processing to ensure consistency and to impute missing values.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The overall response rate for the census, that is the proportion of the population who were included on a census form, was estimated to be 94% in England and Wales, 96.1% in Scotland and 95.2% in Northern Ireland.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] This was due to a number of factors: households with no response, households excluding residents from their returns, and addresses not included in the enumeration.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] In Manchester for example 25,000 people from 14,000 addresses were not enumerated because the address database was two years out of date.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The Local Authority with the lowest response was Kensington and Chelsea with 64%.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Hackney had the next lowest response at 72%.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Out of all local authorities, the ten lowest response rates were all in London.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The results still represent 100 per cent of the population, however, because some individuals not completing their forms were instead identified by census enumerators, and through the use of cross-matching with a follow-up survey.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The results from the 2001 census were produced using a methodology known as the One Number Census.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] This was an attempt to adjust the census counts and impute answers to allow for estimated under-enumeration measured by the Census Coverage Survey (sample size 320,000 households), resulting in a single set of population estimates.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Although the 1851 census had included a question about religion on a separate response sheet, whose completion was not compulsory, the 2001 census was the first in Great Britain to ask about the religion of respondents on the main census form.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] An amendment to the 1920 Census Act (the Census (Amendment) Act 2000) was passed by Parliament to allow the question to be asked, and to allow the response to this question to be optional.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The inclusion of the question enabled the Jedi census phenomenon to take place in the United Kingdom.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] In England and Wales 390,127 people stated their religion as Jedi, as did 14,052 people in Scotland.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] 15% declared themselves of no religion (including Jedi at 0.7%, more than those who declared themselves as Sikh, Jewish or Buddhist) and 8% did not respond to the question.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Since the UK census relies on self-completion, the composition of the other ethnic group category is not fixed.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Analysis by the Office for National Statistics of the 220,000 people in England and Wales who ticked the other ethnic group box in the 2001 census reveals that 53 per cent were born in the Far East, 10 per cent in the UK, 10 per cent in the Middle East, and 7 per cent in Africa.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] People could write in an ethnic group under the 'other' heading.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] 26 per cent did not specify an ethnicity, but of the remainder 23 per cent wrote Filipino, 21 per cent Japanese, 11 per cent Vietnamese, 11 per cent Arab, 6 per cent Middle Eastern and 4 per cent North African.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Controversy surrounding the classification of ethnic groups began as early as 2000, when it was revealed that respondents in Scotland and Northern Ireland would be able to check a box describing themselves as Scottish or Irish, an option not available for English respondents.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] With an absence of an English tick-box, the only other tickbox available was "white-British", "Irish", or "other".
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] However, if 'English' was written in under the "any other white background" it was not clear whether it would be counted as an ethnic group in same the way as the Welsh.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Following criticism, English was included as a tick-box option in the 2011 census.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] It is sometimes claimed that the 2001 census revealed that two-thirds of the population of Wales described themselves as of Welsh nationality.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] In fact, the 2001 census did not collect any information on nationality.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Controversy surrounding the classification of ethnic group began as early as 2000, when it was revealed that respondents in Scotland and Northern Ireland would be able to check a box describing themselves as Scottish or Irish, an option not available for Welsh respondents.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Prior to the census, *Plaid Cymru* backed a petition calling for the inclusion of a Welsh tickbox and for the National Assembly for Wales to have primary law-making powers and its own National Statistics Office.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] With an absence of a Welsh tickbox, the only other tickbox available was "white-British", "Irish", or "other".
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] For the first time in a UK census, those wishing to describe their ethnicity as Cornish were given their own code number (06) on the 2001 UK census form, alongside those for people wishing to describe themselves as English, Welsh, Irish or Scottish.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] About 34,000 people in Cornwall and 3,500 people in the rest of the UK wrote on their census forms in 2001 that they considered their ethnic group to be Cornish.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] This represented nearly 7% of the population of Cornwall.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Various Cornish organisations were campaigning for the inclusion of the Cornish tick box on the next census in 2011.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] A census of the population of the United Kingdom is taken every ten years.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The **2011 census** was held in all countries of the UK on 27 March 2011.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] It was the first UK census which could be completed online via the Internet.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Office for National Statistics (ONS) is responsible for the census in England and Wales, the General Register Office for Scotland (GROS) is responsible for the census in Scotland, and the Northern Ireland Statistics and Research Agency (NISRA) is responsible for the census in Northern Ireland.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Office for National Statistics is the executive office of the UK Statistics Authority, a non-ministerial department formed in 2008 and which reports directly to Parliament.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] ONS is the UK Government's single largest statistical producer of independent statistics on the UK's economy and society, used to assist the planning and allocation of resources, policy-making and decision-making.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] ONS designs, manages and runs the census in England and Wales.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In its capacity as the national statistics office for the United Kingdom, ONS also compiles and releases census tables for the United Kingdom when the data from England and Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland are complete.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In the run-up to the census both the main UK political parties expressed concerns about the increasing cost and the value for money of the census, and it was suggested that the 2011 census might be the last decennial census to be taken.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The first results from the 2011 census, age and sex, and occupied households estimates for England and Wales and Northern Ireland, were released on 16 July 2012.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The first results for Scotland, and the first UK-wide results, were published on 17 December 2012.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] More detailed and specialised data were published from 2013.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Registrar General John Rickman conducted the first census of Great Britain's population, and was responsible for the ten-yearly reports published between 1801 and 1831.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] During the first 100 years of census-taking the population of England and Wales grew more than threefold, to around 32 million, and that of Scotland, where a separate census has been carried out since 1861, to about 4.5 million.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] From 1911 onwards rapid social change, scientific breakthroughs, and major world events affected the structure of the population.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] A fire that destroyed census records in 1931, and the declaration of war in 1939, made the 1951 census hugely significant in recording 30 years of change over one of the most turbulent periods in British history.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 1971 census was run by the newly created Office of Population Censuses and Surveys (OPCS), a body formed by the merger of the General Register Office and Government Social Survey.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In 1996 the Office for National Statistics (ONS) was formed by merging the Central Statistical Office (CSO), OPCS and the statistics division of the Department of Employment; the first census it ran was in 2001.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In 2008 the UK Statistics Authority was established as an independent body.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] A population census is a key instrument for assessing the needs of local communities.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] When related to other data sources such as housing or agricultural censuses, or sample surveys, the data becomes even more useful.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Most countries of the world take censuses: the United Nations recommends that countries take a census at least once every ten years.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Twenty-one out of 40 countries in Europe are engaged in the 2010–2011 census round The design for the 2011 census reflected changes in society since 2001 and asked questions to help paint a detailed demographic picture of England and Wales, as it stood on census day, 27 March 2011.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Data collected by the census is used to provide statistical outputs which central government uses to plan and allocate local authority services funding, and which local authorities themselves use to identify and meet the needs of their local communities.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Other organisations that use census data include healthcare organisations, community groups, researchers and businesses.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The questionnaires, including people's personal information, are kept confidential for 100 years before being released to the public, providing an important source of information for historical, demographic and genealogy research.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 2011 census for England and Wales included around 25 million households.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] People could complete and submit their questionnaire online, or fill it in on paper and post it back in a pre-addressed envelope.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Guidance was provided online and through the census helpline.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Completed questionnaires were electronically tracked and field staff followed up with households that did not return a questionnaire.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In these cases field staff delivered and collected questionnaires and, where needed, provided advice or assistance in completing the questionnaire.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] There was a legal requirement to complete the 2011 census questionnaire, under the terms of the Census Act 1920.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] As at 27 March 2011 everyone who had lived or intended to live in the country for three months or more was required to complete a questionnaire.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Failure to return a completed questionnaire could lead to a fine and criminal record.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Lockheed Martin UK, the UK arm of US-based aerospace, defence, security, and technology company Lockheed Martin was awarded the contract to provide services for the census comprising questionnaire printing, a customer contact centre and data capture and processing.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The contract was valued at £150 million, approximately one third of the total £482 million census budget.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Concerns were raised during contract negotiations that the US PATRIOT Act could be used to force Lockheed Martin to reveal census data to US authorities.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Several groups called for a boycott of the census over the involvement of Lockheed Martin, including the Stop the War Coalition, and the Christian thinktank Ekklesia.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The groups were concerned about sharing data with a company involved in surveillance and data processing for the CIA and FBI; and also providing funding to an arms company making nuclear missiles and cluster bombs.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Green Party also objected, and campaigned unsuccessfully to stop Lockheed Martin getting the contract, although no decision was made about whether or not to call for a boycott.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Census Alert campaign group also decided against calling for a boycott.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Liberal Conspiracy said a boycott would be counter-productive, as the census is used to distribute funding to local services.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Liberal Conspiracy reports that a council may lose £22,000 over 10 years for each person who does not complete the census.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The census for England and Wales was trialled in 135,000 households in Lancaster, the London Borough of Newham and Anglesey on 11 October 2009.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] A test was also carried out in Birmingham at the same time.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The questions for the 2011 census were the same as those trialled in the 2009 Census Rehearsal.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Order for the 2011 Census (including the proposed question topics, census date and who should complete the questionnaire) was laid before Parliament in October 2009 and was approved by Parliament and became law in December 2009.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Capita Group was contracted by ONS to recruit, train and administer the pay for the 35,000 temporary ONS workers who worked as field staff for the 2011 census.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The total cost of the 2011 census in England and Wales over the period from 2004/05 to 2015/16 is estimated to be £482 million.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] This is more than twice the £210m spent on the 2001 census.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] This breaks down to a cost of 87 pence per person, per year (over the life of the census – ten years).
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] "The cost equates to about 87p a year per person, demonstrating excellent value for money.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The per capita costs in the UK are less than for many other European countries that carry out similar censuses.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In summary, this census will meet crucial requirements for statistical information that Government and others cannot do without." Minister of State, Cabinet Office (Angela E.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Both the main UK political parties had expressed concerns about the rising costs and value of a ten-yearly census, and on coming into office the UK coalition government had gone as far as suggesting that the 2011 census might be the last of its kind.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In July 2010 the UK government asked ONS to explore other methods of measuring the population.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In 2011 the three national statistics bodies, ONS, GROS and NISRA set up a co-ordinated research project known as Beyond 2011.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The project reported its findings in March 2014 and recommended that a UK-wide census in 2021 should take place, and that better use should be made of other demographic data sources.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The general style of the questionnaire was similar to that of the 2001 census.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] A rehearsal questionnaire was released in 2009.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Several new identity and status options were included for the first time.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In 2001 only 38 people were reported to have been prosecuted for refusing to complete a questionnaire.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In 2011 those who refused to complete the census questionnaire or included false information could face a fine of up to £1,000.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] A team of compliance staff were recruited to follow up by visiting those householders who refused to complete a questionnaire or where their questionnaire was not returned or completed correctly.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Advertising promoted the notion of how the UK 2011 census would help to shape Britain's future in areas such as healthcare and education.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] TV adverts, for example, depicted Origami, in census colours, forming objects including school computers and buses.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] A short sentence under the census logo informed the viewer that the census was a duty that must be undertaken.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] From 7 April 2011 advertising focused on reminding people to complete and return by post or submit online.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] A question about the number of bedrooms a household has, as well as the names, gender and birth dates of any overnight guests was criticised as "bedroom snooping" by the Conservative Party in opposition.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Although some 37,000 people recorded their identity as Cornish by manually writing it on the form in the 2001 census, no tick-box was provided in 2011 to select Cornish as a White British national identity, despite campaigns.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] As a consequence, posters were created by the census organisation and Cornwall Council which advised residents of how they could identify themselves as Cornish by writing it in the ethnicity, national identity and main language sections.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Additionally, people could record Cornwall as their country of birth.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] During the consultation on the 2011 census the British Humanist Association raised several concerns about question 20, "What is your religion?".
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The BHA argued it was a leading question, and suggested that it should be phrased as two questions, "Do you have a religion?" and "If so, what is it?".
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] It contended that by placing the religion question near the ethnicity question it would encourage some responders to associate religion with cultural identity.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The BHA also ran adverts during March 2011 encouraging the use of the 'no religion' box in the questionnaire.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 2011 census for Northern Ireland had 59 questions in total.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] 14 were about the household and its accommodation and 45 questions were for each individual member of the household to complete.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The rehearsal was held on Sunday 11 October 2009 in two areas, Derriaghy and Moy & Benburb, covering approximately 5,000 households.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 2011 census for Northern Ireland costing around £21.8 million over the six-year period 2008–2014.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Over the ten-year cycle the cost is expected to be about £25 million.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In Scotland, a wholly owned subsidiary of information technology company CACI was contracted to gather information.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] CACI "provided interrogators who worked at Abu Ghraib prison at the height of the prisoner abuse scandal".
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 2011 Scotland census asked 13 household questions and up to 35 questions for each individual.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Plans were rehearsed in west Edinburgh and Lewis and Harris.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 2011 census was the first to include a question asking about the ability to read, write and understand the Scots language alongside the question for ability in Scottish Gaelic and English languages.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Responsibility for the release of data from the 2011 census is split between the Office for National Statistics (ONS) for England and Wales, the General Register Office for Scotland (GROS) for Scotland and the Northern Ireland Statistics and Research Agency (NISRA).
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The ONS announced in March the release plan for the results of the 2011 census which stated in July 2012.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] NISRA made a similar announcement with identical release plan.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In June 2012 GROS advised on its release plan which commences in December 2012.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The releases will comprise data sets enabling the standard comparison with previous census data reports as well as over a hundred new data sets based on the new questions asked in the 2011 census.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] NISRA, ONS and GROS each publish a schedule stating what documents they will release and when.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Those documents are called a "prospectus".
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Each prospectus is not fixed, but changes as schedules are changed or documents are late.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The prospectuses are linked to in the table below.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Office for National Statistics is responsible for publishing United Kingdom wide 2011 census data.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] These are co-ordinated releases coinciding with data published by the three national statistical authorities.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population data including data for males and females for the United Kingdom and revised estimates England, Northern Ireland, Scotland and Wales.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population numbers (rounded), by five-year age bands, sex and densities and household sata at national and local authority level.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population estimates (unrounded) by single year of age and sex for the UK and all local authorities (or equivalent) in the UK, along with UK historic population pyramids (1951–2011).
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and Quick statistics Part 1 – Census Profiles; Population, People and Places, Health and Social Care, Travel and Transport.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] National and Local Authority geographies.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and Quick statistics Part 2 – Census Profiles; Qualifications and Labour Market.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and Quick statistics Part 3 – Multivariate, Local and Detailed Characteristics tables for: Living arrangements; Household composition; and Accommodation type.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] A series of further releases, subsequent to the four main releases of 2011 Census statistics including migration tables, workplace tables, detailed religion and ethnic group tables, and statistics relating to alternative population bases.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Specialist products would include:- Small population groups; microdata; flow data (also known as origin-destination statistics).
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] It is also suggested that data organised around alternative population bases may be produced.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The original plans of the ONS, covering England and Wales, confirmed that there would be four stages of data release starting in July 2012 and running until October 2013.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] This was increased to five stages in October 2013.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] A detailed commentary accompanies each release along with relevant reference materials.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Additionally there will be graphic visualisations providing further clarification and comparison between different data sets and comparison over time using data from earlier censuses.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] There will also be more specialist reports and products.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Certain data bases will also be produced in the Welsh language.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick univariate (single parameter) statistics based on output levels, with release based on geography.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] (e.g. local authority, wards and parish/ community) tabulated by population count and percentages and accessible by post code.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key Statistics for local authorities in England and Wales comprising data which adds detail to the population estimates published in July 2012.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] It includes population information on international migration, age, ethnicity, national identity, health, housing and religion.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] For Wales, there is data on the Welsh language and population data on unitary authorities.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Statistical tables for Output Areas (OAs) and for wards.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Background information covering families, general health and disability, unpaid care, language, occupation and industry, qualifications and economic activity.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick statistics for postcode sectors, health areas and Welsh Government devolved constituencies, and the key statistics for national parks in England and Wales, with a separate release for Wales only.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Statistical tables for non-UK short-term residents in England and Wales and quick statistics for England and Wales on national identity, passports held and country of birth, with a separate release for Wales only.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] More detailed cross tabulation of data topics: Migration; ethnicity, identity, language and religion; health; and Welsh tables.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Detailed Characteristics tables for the themes of demography and families at local authority, MSOA and ward level.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] English language proficiency for regions, local authorities, 2011 Census Merged Wards and MSOAs in England and Wales.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The first Local Characteristics tables for the topics of ethnicity, identity, language and religion for Output Areas, unitary and local authorities and regions.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Local Characteristics tables for the topics of health and unpaid care for Output Areas.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Follow up to Release 3.2b on 12 July 2013.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Local Characteristic Tables for the topic of migration for Output Areas.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Local Characteristics on travel to work and car and van availability for Output Areas.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In addition to the six main releases phases further supplementary, smaller scale and specialist releases including; Small population groups, Microdata (teaching files, safeguarded files and secure files), Origin-destination data, and Alternate population bases.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The release plans for Northern Ireland were set out by the NISRA.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The release phases are closely synchronised with those of the ONS for England and Wales with some marginal variations to allow for local administrative arrangements.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Usual resident population by single age and sex.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Usual resident population by single age and sex for Local Government Districts, etc.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Household number and size by geographic units.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key statistics for NI and Local Government Districts etc.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Quick statistics for all geographies and population and household estimates for lower geographies.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Detailed characteristics for NI-wide and all local authority and other geographies (including religion, identity and health).
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Detailed characteristics for NI (including ethnicity, country of birth and language).
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Remaining detailed characteristics for NI including labour market and housing.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] All outstanding detailed characteristics for the remaining geographic areas.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Multivariate local characteristic tables and detailed themes around: economic activity; country of birth; occupation; and unpaid care.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The release plans for Scotland were set out by the GROS Release phase dates are partly in sync with those of the other UK constituent country statistical authorities, however the first release was scheduled for six months after the first releases by the other authorities.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Consequently, release of UK-wide data has been scheduled so as to coincide with release plans for Scotland's Census releases.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population estimates, based on resident households, communal establishments and age bands.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Estimates of the usually resident population of Scotland rounded to the nearest thousand, broken down by age and sex.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] An estimate of the total population in each council area, rounded to nearest thousand.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population estimates by five-year age bands and sex for Scotland and each council area.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population and household changes since 2001 census.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population dependency ratios for Scotland and each council area.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] First release of unrounded population estimates and household communal establishment numbers, by single year of age and sex.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] (First published as rounded data in December 2012 and March 2013).
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick statistics; Census Profiles; headcounts and geography products.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Comprising; Estimates by postcode and geography products.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] This release will represent the start of the dissemination of detailed census statistics for small areas.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick statistics tables for marriage and civil partnership, ethnicity, religion, language proficiency, country of birth and national identity, heath (excluding long-term health), age, arrival in UK, population and households, housing and accommodation, car and van ownership.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Coverage: Scotland, Council Areas and Health Boards.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick statistics tables for Education and Labour Market.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Coverage: All output areas and Data Zones.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Also the key and quick statistics for the remaining geographies of the topics covered in Release 2a.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick statistics tables for Living Arrangements and Travel to Work Methods.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Coverage: All levels of census geographies.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Multivariate statistics, comprising a combination of; age, sex, resident type, ethnic group, economic activity, general health and provision of unpaid care, country of birth, and occupation.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Local and Detailed Characteristics tables for Qualifications, Employment and Economic Activity, Travel for Work and Study.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Local and Detailed Characteristics tables including; Travel to Work, Household, Qualifications and Long-term Health, Social Status and Economic Activity.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The United Kingdom Statistics Authority is responsible for coordinating the release of census data by the devolved statistics authorities.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] It publishes UK-wide census data results via the Office for National Statistics (ONS) site.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The UK Data Service provides a central point of reference for all country-specific census data releases via its Learning Hub site.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Primary responsibility for country-specific 2011 census data rests with the statistical authorities for each of the UK's constituent countries.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Each authority has at least one dedicated central source from which data can be downloaded or ordered.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] For England and Wales the ONS provides the access to primary data via its 2011 census siteArchived 29 January 2016 at the UK Government Web Archive.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Additionally, data organised by local authority or post code is available on the Neighbourhood Statistics Archived 20 October 2010 at the Wayback Machine site, and nomis, a source of detailed census results which can be assembled into bespoke data sets.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] For Scotland the General Registrar Office for Scotland (GROS) part of National Records of Scotland (NRS) to maintain access via its Scotlands Census site, and for Northern Ireland the Statistics and Research Authority (NISRA) uses the Northern Ireland Neighbourhood Information Service (NINIS).
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The format of all the pre-defined statistical tables is standardised as far as practical across the publishing authorities.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Since the 2001 UK census the naming conventions for the tables have been revised following research into the approaches adopted by other census publishing bodies around the world.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The statistical authorities are also making available bulk data in Comma-separated values (CSV) file format which can be downloaded from online data warehouse facilities.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In addition to the standard releases and online bulk access the statistical authorities provide a commissioned data service whereby other data configurations can be purchased, under license, by customers and will subsequently be made freely available to other users.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The **2021–2022 United Kingdom censuses** collectively comprised the 23rd census of the United Kingdom.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The censuses of England and Wales, and Northern Ireland took place on 21 March 2021, and the census of Scotland took place later on 20 March 2022.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The censuses were administered by the Office for National Statistics (ONS) in England and Wales, by the Northern Ireland Statistics and Research Agency (NISRA) in Northern Ireland, and by the National Records of Scotland in Scotland.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] These were the first UK censuses for which most of the data was gathered online.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Two of the censuses went ahead despite the COVID-19 pandemic, in part because the information obtained would assist government and public understanding of the pandemic's impact.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The census in Scotland was postponed, and took place in 2022.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The censuses in 2021 and 2022 follow on from Beyond 2011, a project by the UK Statistics Authority to assess the value, cost, and alternatives to running a census in England and Wales in 2021.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The project recommended an England and Wales census be held in 2021, and that it be conducted predominantly by means of online returns.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Initial results for England and Wales were released on 28 June 2022, while initial results for Scotland were released on 14 September 2023.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] After the 2011 census, both the UK coalition government and the main opposition party, Labour, expressed concerns about the rising costs of the decadal census.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] There were also concerns about the value of continuing with the traditional approach adopted for the 2011 census.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] This included whether collection methods were still fit for purpose in a rapidly changing society and whether census outputs, based on a survey conducted every ten years, would continue to meet the increasingly demanding needs of public and private sector users.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Emerging technological developments were seen as providing alternative and improved data gathering opportunities.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] These concerns and opportunities led the UK Government to question if a supplementary or wholly alternative approach to the traditional 10-yearly census was required; more frequent, possibly annual, small-scale surveys could be employed instead.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] In 2011, The Beyond 2011 Programme was established to look at alternatives to the traditional census approach.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The UK Statistics Authority coordinated the project which was also undertaken by its counterparts in the devolved administrations of Scotland and Northern Ireland.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Existing census gathering methods would be used only as an alternative, where online methods are not feasible.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] A parallel announcement for Scotland's 2021 census was made by the National Records for Scotland.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The ONS Director, Population and Demography Statistics was reported as saying that an estimated 60–65% of household returns would be completed online.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] In April 2014, the British House of Commons Public Accounts Committee (PAC) concluded in its report *Too soon to scrap the Census*, that the 2021 census should go ahead.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] It had reservations over the lack of investigation into the options for using administrative data and encouraged the UK Government to reassure the public about privacy concerns.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The Minister for the Cabinet Office welcomed the recommendations for a predominantly online 2021 census for England and Wales supplemented by the use of governmental and other administrative data in a letter to the National Statistician in July 2014.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Under the Census Act 1920, it is for the United Kingdom Government and Parliament to determine the arrangements for census-taking in England and Wales.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Parallel legislative procedures will be required in the devolved administrations of Scotland and Northern Ireland.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] It would be late 2015 at the earliest before regulations were made.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Subject to this legislation being passed the census would be conducted on the same day in England and Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland to ensure coherence and consistency.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] There is a legal requirement to complete the 2011 census questionnaire, under the terms of the Census Act 1920.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] As at 21 March 2021 everyone who had lived or intended to live in the country for three months or more was required to complete a questionnaire.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] In Scotland, the Census (Amendment) (Scotland) Act 2019 made provisions for voluntary questions about transgender status and sexual orientation to be asked.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The Census (Return Particulars and Removal of Penalties) Act 2019 makes the same provision for England and Wales.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The sexual orientation question would also be asked in Northern Ireland.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The campaign 'If you're not religious, say so!' by Humanists UK aimed to change the wording of the census question on religion.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] This campaign encouraged non-religious people to tick 'no religion' in order to create a more accurate portrayal of religiousness in the UK.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Another campaign by the Climate Census campaign group suggested writing in 'Climate concerned' in response to the religion question, to demand climate action from the government.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The Office for National Statistics published an online guidance titled *What is your Sex* for the 2021 census.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The guidance provided that a respondent should answer according to official documents such as their passport.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Self-identification is already recognised in some countries.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] A gender marker on a British passport can be changed in a less formal procedure than acquiring a legally enforceable gender recognition certificate.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] In March 2021, Fair Play for Women, an anti-transgender campaign group against self-identification, applied for judicial review in England and Wales and argued that such incidental self-identification should not be allowed in census-taking.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] In the absence of opposition or intervention from any interested party, the judge ordered an interim revision of the guidance.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The government conceded and accepted the order.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The ONS withdrew from the High Court proceedings.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Some academics criticised what they said was the ONS's confusion between the concepts of sex and gender identity.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Other academics supported the design of the census questions, for example, on the ground that the transgender population is very small.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] In Scotland, similar pieces of guidance have been published since the previous census in 2011.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The Scottish Parliament also sought to amend the census Act in 2019 to clarify the meaning of sex in that legislation to include gender identity.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The plan was abandoned and changes were instead made in subordinate legislation.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] In August 2021, National Records of Scotland issued guidelines regarding the sex question in the 2022 Scottish census.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The guidance states that "If you are transgender the answer you give can be different from what is on your birth certificate.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] You do not need a Gender Recognition Certificate (GRC)".
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The UK Statistics Authority wrote to National Records of Scotland to question the guidelines.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] In December 2021, Fair Play for Women applied for a judicial review in Scotland.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Lord Sandison dismissed the case on 17 February 2022 stating that there was "no general rule or principle of law that a question as to a person's sex may only properly be answered by reference to the sex stated on that person's birth certificate or GRC".
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] An appeal by Fair Play for Women was refused by the Inner House of the Court of Session.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The UK Statistics Authority has the responsibility for coordinating the census arrangements across the United Kingdom through the Office for National Statistics (ONS), which is also responsible for the census in England and Wales.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The 2011 UK census was the first decennial census in the United Kingdom to include the option of completing the census documentation online.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Across the UK between 15 and 19% of census forms were submitted online.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The UK Statistics Authority proposed that the 2021 census should be conducted predominantly online (with support provided for those unable to complete the census online), supplemented by the use of administrative and survey data and improve annual statistics between censuses.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] For the census in 2021 the proposed target for online completion has been set to at least 65%.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Research has been under way since 2011 to design a new census methodology which maximises the success of an online approach.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Issues identified also included the accuracy of administrative data sets for geographical areas below that of local authorities, problems associated with estimation and the use of address registers.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The UK Statistics Authority has commissioned research strands as part of a census transformation programme which was due to report by 2017 relating to the 2021 census operation, the shape of population statistics in 2021, and the shape of population statistics beyond 2021 in the lead up to 2031.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] A work programme running until 2024, comprising eight phases, was developed by ONS.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Alongside this programme trials of statistics generation using administrative data were planned starting from the autumn of 2015 and running through to 2021 with the aim of ranging across the breadth, detail and accuracy of census outputs.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The contract for preparing, dispatching up to 16 million paper questionnaire packs (for anyone who did not want to, or could not access the census online), and then securely managing, capturing and digitising the responses was awarded to Leidos Innovations UK.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The contract was estimated to be worth around £65.1m.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The parent company of Leidos Innovations UK, Leidos (an American defence, aviation, information technology, and biomedical research company), merged with Lockheed Martin's IT sector in August 2016.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Lockheed Martin UK was awarded the contract for the census in 2011.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Adecco UK was contracted by ONS to recruit, train and administer the pay for the 30,000 temporary ONS workers who would be working as field staff for the 2021 census.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] An advertising campaign (made under contract by M&C Saatchi) was launched under the slogan of "it's about us" at the start of 2021.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Television adverts tried to show a diverse range of people in various locations in England and Wales in front of a purple fabric screen, with a cover version of The Zombies' "This Will Be Our Year", performed by Jose McGill & The Vagaband, featuring as the advert soundtrack.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The Northern Ireland Statistics and Research Agency (NISRA) undertakes the census in Northern Ireland.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The National Records of Scotland (NRS) is responsible for the census in Scotland.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] A rehearsal was conducted on 7 October 2019 and closed for returns on 7 November 2019 in three local authority areas: parts of Glasgow City, Dumfries and Galloway and Na h-Eileanan Siar.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The census was scheduled to take place on 21 March 2021, but was delayed in July 2020 by the Scottish Government because of the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The Scottish Government has come under criticism for the way the census has been conducted, with some news outlets describing the results as being "botched" due to record low turnout rates and failing to meet the set target return rate of 94%.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Initial turnout rates for the census in Scotland concluded with 79% return rate; an additional round of extension to filling out the census was granted to encourage returns, raising the return rate percentage to 89%.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The return rate for comparison in England and Wales was 97%.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] However national statistician Ian Diamond has said that despite not meeting the target, the census could still provide "really good data".
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The additional round of extension cost the Scottish Government an additional £6m, and £148m in total.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Although it is a Crown Dependency and not part of the United Kingdom, Jersey carried out a census on the same day as the 2021 censuses in England and Wales, and Northern Ireland.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Guernsey no longer carries out a decennial census, instead using the Rolling Electronic Census Project to produce regular census reports.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The Isle of Man also undertook a full census in 2021 (having held an interim census in 2016).
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Initial results, released in June 2022, showed the recorded population of England and Wales to be 59,597,300 (56,489,800 in England and 3,107,500 in Wales), a rise of 6.3% or 3.5 million people over the previous decade.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] This was the largest population ever recorded through a census in England and Wales, and the overall population of the United Kingdom was estimated to be 67 million.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The census also showed that the population of the two countries, aged 65 and over, had surpassed the number of children aged 15 and under for the first time, with 11.1 million people aged 65 and over compared with 10.4 million aged under 15.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Results of the question on religion were published on 29 November 2022.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The question was voluntary but was answered by 94.0% of the population of England and Wales.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] 46.2% of the population described themselves as "Christian", 6.5% as "Muslim", and 1.7% as "Hindu".
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] 37.2% of the population asserted that they had "no religion".
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] In Wales, there were more people declaring that they had "no religion" (47%) than those affirming a Christian identity or any other religion.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Results on sexual orientation and gender identity questions were released on 6 January 2023.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Similarly to the religion question, this question was voluntary but was answered by 92.5% of the population of England and Wales.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] 89.4% of the population described themselves as straight or heterosexual, 1.5% described themselves as "Gay or lesbian", 1.3% as "Bisexual" and 0.3% were described as having "[an]other sexual orientation" (with the most common being pansexual, asexual and queer).
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] 0.5% answered 'No' to the census question 'Is the gender you identify with the same as your sex registered at birth?' Alice Sullivan, professor of sociology at University College London, reported that in the 16 to 24 age group, 1% answered 'No' to the question.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] She said that females were more likely than males to answer 'No' in that age group, whereas in other age groups females were more likely to answer 'Yes'.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] In April 2023, when more granular data became available, Michael Biggs, professor of sociology at the University of Oxford, complained about what he perceived to be anomalies in the data on the 0.5% who identified as transgender, when disaggregated by local authority and other factors.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] He questioned whether the ONS had adequately tested the gender identity question with respondents for whom English is a second language.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The Office for Statistics Regulation (OSR), which oversees the ONS, began an examination of Biggs' concerns about the statistics, including the reported result that 262,000 identify as transgender in England and Wales.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] An anonymous government source said they believed the number 260,000 of transgender people was "hugely overstated".
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] In September 2024, the OSR removed official accreditation of the gender identity statistics, classifying them instead as official statistics in development.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Results for Northern Ireland were published by the Northern Ireland Statistics and Research Agency in Spring 2023.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] National Records of Scotland published the first results on 14 September 2023.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The results showed that Scotland's population was 5,436,600, the highest figure on record but a slower rate of population growth, 2.7% since 2011, than the previous growth of 4.6%.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The first results, in May 2024, were population estimates at output areas, as well as topical data about ethnic group, national identity, language and religion.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The rest of the data was published across 2024 and into 2025.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The low response rates (88%) compared with the rest of the UK mean that the data is only partial so does not fully reflect the state of Scotland's demographics.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The census showed there were 2,509,300 households in Scotland with at least one usual resident.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] There were some 930,000 single person households in Scotland and over a third of all households were single person (37.1%).
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The census revealed that over half a million people living in Scotland were born in the rest of the UK (563,500).
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Furthermore, that a further half a million were born outside of the UK (554,900).
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The number of people born outside of the UK had increased by 185,600 since 2011.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The census showed the population as ageing, with over one million people aged 65 and over (1,091,000).
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The number of people under 15 was only 832,300.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The majority of people said they had no religion.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Of those who were religious in 2022, 20.4% responded ‘Church of Scotland', 13.3% ‘Roman Catholic’, 5.1% 'Other Christian' and 2.2% 'Muslim'.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Among those who selected 'Other Christian,' 72,359 people identified as Anglican or Episcopalian.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] In 2022 the census results showed 12.9% of people in Scotland had a minority ethnic background.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] 77.7% described themselves as 'Scottish', 9.4% as 'Other British'.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] The **3rd Karmapa, Rangjung Dorje** (Tibetan: རང་འབྱུང་རྡོ་རྗེ་, Wylie: rang 'byung rdo rje) (1284–1339) was the 3rd Gyalwa Karmapa and head of the Karma Kagyu school, the largest school within the Kagyu tradition.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] He was an important figure in the history of Tibetan Buddhism, who helped to spread Buddha-nature teachings in Tibet.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] Rangjung Dorjé was officially recognized as the first tulku, the reincarnation of Karma Pakshi, in 1282.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] The 3rd Karmapa was raised at the Tsurphu Monastery, where he received teachings from both the Kagyu and Nyingma traditions from eminent masters such as Trophu Künden Sherab and Nyenre Gendün Bum.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] He became renowned as one of the greatest masters of his time and had a large number of disciples.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] He undertook a spiritual retreat on the slopes of Everest, received full ordination, and completed his studies at a significant Kadampa teaching center.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] Rangjung Dorje visited China, where the emperor Toghon Temur became his disciple.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] Upon his death, Rangjung Dorje's face is said to have appeared in the moon there.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] As a tulku lineage, the Karmapas were among the earliest recognized Tulkus, reincarnated as deities.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] The first Karmapas were influential in the Mongolian Yuan and Chinese Ming courts as well as the Tangut Western Xia Kingdom.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] Through visions, he is believed to have received teachings on the "Wheel of Time", the Kalachakra.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] In 1284 he authored an astrological compendium entitled *The Compendium of Astrology* (Tib.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] *rtsis kun bsdus pa*), from which a Tibetan calendar was developed by the lineage of the Gyalwang Karmapas.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] Called the Tsurphu tradition calendar or the Tsurluk calendar, his astrological compendium was the basis from which many treatises authored by the subsequent Karmapas and by Jamgon Kongtrul the Great evolved.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] The Tsurluk calendar is still used by the Karma Kagyu and overseen by Tsipa Gelek Dhargay, at the 17th Karmapa, Ogyen Trinley Dorje's seat in Rumtek, Sikkim, India.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] Rangjung Dorje was also known as a great practitioner of Traditional Tibetan medicine.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] Born to a Nyingma family, Rangjung Dorje was a lineage-holder in both the Karma Kagyu and the Nyingma tradition of Dzogchen.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] He was a disciple of the Nyingma master Rigdzin Kumaradza Shönnu Gyelpo (Tibetan: rig 'dzin ku ma ra dza gzhon nu rgyal po; 1266–1343) who passed on to him the "heart-essence" (nying-thig) teachings transmitted by Padmasambhava and Vimalamitra (the Khandro Nyingtik and Vima Nyingtik respectively).
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] He also encountered the Nyingma master Longchenpa, who transmitted to him certain Dzogchen teachings.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] In exchange, Rangjung Dorje imparted important "New Translation" Tantras to Longchenpa.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] Rangjung Dorje was also a "Treasure revealer" of termas.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] The Karma Kagyu Dzogchen transmission that arose from his lineage is known as the "Karma-Nyingthig" (Tibetan: kar ma snying thig; Essence of the Heart of the Karma School).
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] In 1321 the famous scholar Dolpopa (1292–1361) visited Tsurphu Monastery for the first time and had extensive discussions with Rangjung Dorje about doctrinal issues.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] It appears that Rangjung Dorje almost certainly influenced the development of some of Dolpopa's theories, possibly including his Zhentong (*gzhan stong*) method.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] According to Karma phrin las, *Dri lan yid*, 91-92, his teacher, Chödrak Gyatso, the Seventh Karmapa, interpreted the nature of Zhentong (*gzhan stong*) accepted by Rangjung Dorje.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] 15) conveys that the Third Karmapa was a systematizer of the Chöd developed by Machig Labdrön and lists a number of his works on Chod consisting of redactions, outlines and commentaries.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] Yungtön Dorjepel (1284–1365), (the previous incarnation of the First Panchen Lama, Khedrup Je), studied the Great Perfection due to the great inspiration of Rangjung Dorje.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] Rangjung Dorje was a noted scholar who composed many significant texts, the most famous of which is the *Profound Inner Meaning* (Wylie: *zab mo nang don*), which concern the Vajrayana inner yoga practices.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/buddhism-in-scotland] The earliest Buddhist influence on Scotland came through its imperial connections with South East Asia, and as a result the early connections were with the Theravada traditions of Burma, Thailand, and Sri Lanka.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/buddhism-in-scotland] To begin with, 150 years ago, this response was primarily scholarly, and a tradition of study grew up that eventually resulted in the foundation of the Pali Text Society, which undertook the huge task of translating the Pali Canon of Theravada Buddhist texts into English.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/buddhism-in-scotland] The rate of growth was slow but steady through the century, and the 1950s saw the development of interest in Zen Buddhism.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/buddhism-in-scotland] In 1967 Kagyu Samyé Ling Monastery and Tibetan Centre was founded by Tibetan lamas and refugees Chögyam Trungpa Rinpoche and Akong Rinpoche.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/buddhism-in-scotland] It is in Eskdalemuir, in south west Scotland and is the largest Tibetan Buddhist centre in Western Europe, and part of the Karma Kagyu tradition.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/buddhism-in-scotland] As well there are other Buddhism-based new religious movements such as the New Kadampa Tradition, Triratna Buddhist Community and Sōka Gakkai International.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/buddhism-in-scotland] The Triratna community maintains a retreat centre at Balquhidder in the Trossachs.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/buddhism-in-scotland] In the 2001 census, there were 6,830 Buddhists in Scotland, or 0.1% of the population.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/buddhism-in-scotland] This increased to 12,795 people, or 0.2%, in the 2011 census.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/buddhism-in-scotland] Kagyu Samyé Ling Monastery and Tibetan Centre was founded in 1967 by two spiritual masters, Choje Akong Tulku Rinpoche and Chogyam Trungpa Rinpoche, who both belong to the Kagyu school of Tibetan Buddhism.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/buddhism-in-scotland] It was the first Tibetan Buddhist Centre to be established in the West and was named after Samye, the very first monastery to be established in Tibet.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/buddhism-in-scotland] In 1977, during the 16th Karmapa's second visit to Samye Ling, he assured Akong Rinpoche about the longer-term future of Buddhism in the West and at Samye Ling.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/buddhism-in-scotland] It is from this encounter that the Samye Project was born.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/buddhism-in-scotland] There is an associated community on Holy Isle, a small island off the coast of the Isle of Arran, which is owned by Samyé Ling.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/buddhism-in-scotland] The settlements on the island include the *Centre for World Peace and Health* and a traditional retreat centre for nuns.
[src:buddhism-in-scotland/buddhism-in-scotland] Samyé Ling has also established centres in more than 20 countries, including Belgium, Ireland, Poland, South Africa, Spain and Switzerland.
